      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk level.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical R2022 R1 is a commercially validated finite element solver with documented V&V procedures. FDA CDRH internal use is governed by a software quality management plan compliant with 21 CFR Part 11. Version control, audit trails, and regression test suites are maintained. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2 for medium model risk."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Benchmark problems from NAFEMS and ASME V&V 10 test suite were executed to verify linear elastic structural elements, contact formulations, and large-deformation kinematics relevant to pedicle screw bending. All benchmark results within 1% of analytical solutions. Code verification documented in FDA OSEL internal technical report TR-2021-07."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrating QoI change less than 5% between successive refinements.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was performed on the pedicle screw shank and screw-rod interface regions. Coarse (0.5 mm), medium (0.3 mm), and fine (0.15 mm) element sizes were evaluated. Construct stiffness changed by 3.1% between coarse and medium, and 1.4% between medium and fine. Medium mesh adopted for production runs, satisfying the 5% convergence criterion."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual convergence criteria documented and confirmed met for all simulation runs.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson nonlinear solver with force residual tolerance 1e-4 and displacement residual tolerance 1e-5. All 11 simulation runs converged within 50 load increments. No diverged or unconverged solutions observed. Solver log files archived in the simulation data package."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model setup independently reviewed by a second analyst not involved in original model construction.",
      "rationale": "Model geometry, material assignments, boundary conditions, and contact definitions were independently reviewed by a second FDA OSEL engineer. Review checklist completed per internal SOP-FEA-003. Three minor discrepancies identified and corrected prior to final simulation runs. No material errors in final model configuration."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form assumptions documented and justified relative to the COU physics; any simplifications assessed for impact on QoIs.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic material model adopted for titanium alloy screw and UHMWPE rod components, justified by the pre-yield regime of interest. Frictional contact (Coulomb, mu=0.2) at screw-rod interface based on literature values for titanium-on-titanium. Simplified vertebral body block representation (ASTM F1717 compliant) removes biological variability. Model form assumptions reviewed against COU physics and judged appropriate for stiffness and yield force prediction."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All material and geometric input parameters traceable to measured values or certified material data; uncertainty bounds established.",
      "rationale": "Titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) elastic modulus and yield strength sourced from material certificates for the production screw lot. UHMWPE rod modulus from manufacturer datasheet with ±10% uncertainty. Screw geometry from CMM measurements of three production screws. Friction coefficient uncertainty range 0.15–0.30 evaluated in a screening sensitivity study, which identified it as a secondary driver of stiffness (±3.2% QoI sensitivity). All inputs documented in simulation input log."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test specimens traceable to the same production lot as modeled geometry; sample size sufficient for statistical comparison.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs assembled from production-lot non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws and ASTM F1717-compliant test blocks. Specimens distributed across two independent laboratories (FDA OSEL and DePuy Synthes) to assess inter-laboratory variability. Specimen dimensions verified by caliper measurement prior to testing. Sample size of 11 provides sufficient power for E/uval metric at the declared uncertainty level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios or deviation from required level explicitly justified.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under a single load configuration (ASTM F1717 static compression-bending at 5 mm/min). Only one test condition evaluated, which does not span the full range of in vivo loading scenarios (dynamic, torsion, lateral bending). This factor is below the required level 3. The shortfall is acknowledged; the COU is limited to static compression-bending prediction and the acceptance decision reflects this scope limitation."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation input parameters demonstrably equivalent to test conditions within stated uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "Measured specimen dimensions, torque-controlled assembly preload, and actuator displacement rate from bench test protocols were replicated in simulation inputs. Material properties derived from the same production lot as test specimens. Boundary conditions (fixed base block, actuator displacement applied to superior block) mirror ASTM F1717 fixture geometry. Equivalency documented in input-output traceability matrix."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) computed for each QoI; all values within pre-established acceptance bounds.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs compared: construct stiffness (E/uval=0.87), yield force (E/uval=1.31), and force at 40 mm displacement (E/uval=1.02). All E/uval values below the pre-established threshold of 1.96. Simulation uncertainty (uval) computed from mesh convergence, material property uncertainty, and solver tolerance contributions combined in quadrature. Experimental uncertainty from inter-laboratory and inter-specimen variability. Full uncertainty budget documented in validation report VR-2023-COU1."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly linked to the clinical/regulatory decision and to the failure modes of concern.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and directly relevant to the regulatory submission decision. Yield force is the primary failure metric for screw fracture risk assessment. Force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield structural integrity. All three QoIs are mechanistically linked to the clinical concern of screw fracture leading to revision surgery."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities performed on the same device geometry, material, and loading regime as the COU.",
      "rationale": "Validation activities performed on the identical non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw geometry, titanium alloy material, and ASTM F1717 compression-bending loading as the COU. No extrapolation across device geometry, material, or loading mode required. The validation domain is coincident with the COU domain, providing direct relevance without analogy arguments."
    }
